ACINETOBACTER, DRUG RESISTANT - USA EX IRAQ: ALERT
**************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>


[1]
Date: Tue, 22 Jun 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Dooley DP lecture (abstracted)
<http://www.brooks.af.mil/web/af/global2004/04_present/A%20Tale%20of%20Two%20Outbreaks.ppt>


Beginning in Apr 2003, an unusual number of wound infections with
_Acinetobacter_ were noted in USA soldiers evacuated from Iraq to the USS
Comfort (a hospital ship) or Landstuhl Army Medical Center (in
Germany). The numbers were noteworthy, since the infection was not noted
in the 1991 Gulf War and exceeded historical experience of the
centers. Indeed, the USS Comfort exhausted its supply of imipenem, a
carbapenem antimicrobial used to treat infections with this Gram-negative
bacillus.

The numbers reported in this lecture were Walter Reed Army Medical Center
(Washington, DC)14, Landstuhl Army Medical Center 11, National Naval
Medical Center (Bethesda, MD) 6, and Brooke Army Medical Center (TX) 3, for
a total of 34. 55 percent of the isolates were from wounds, 20 percent
from sputum, 10 percent from tissue, 7 percent from blood, 4 percent from
urine and 2 percent each from catheter tips and drains. 97 percent of the
cases were from action in Iraq, primarily involving the forward troops.

The antimicrobial resistance pattern reported was 2 percent sensitive to no
antimicrobials, 41 percent sensitive to only carbapenems, 26 percent
sensitive to carbapenems and one other antimicrobial class, and 31% another
pattern of sensitivity.

[The month through which the data was collected is not stated. - Mod.LL]

