[2]
Date: Tue, 22 Jun 2004 (Accessed)
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Pasquina PF, Gambel J, Scoville C lecture (abstracted)
<http://www.vard.org/meet/Pasquina.pdf>


Walter Reed Army Medical Center experience with Iraq warfare associated
_Acinetobacter baumanii_.

37 of 442 (8.4 percent) medical evacuees were culture-positive.

3 cases identified of nosocomial spread of the multiply resistant organism.

[With 37 patients, this report must be later than the first one. It is not
clearly stated how many of the cases were colonized as opposed to infected.
- Mod. LL]

--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[As was noted in postings below related to the conflict in Iraq a year ago,
polyresistant _Acinetobacter spp._ has been acquired in the field as well
as in nosocomial settings. Infectious disease clinicians even outside the
military and VA settings should be aware of this risk from individuals
returning from active duty.

In my moderation of the previous thread below, I included the following
regarding _Acinetobacter_ infections of wartime injuries (references
renumbered):

Myron Tong reported that _Mimeae-Herellea_ (organisms of which some were
renamed _Acinetobacter_) were the most common Gram-negative bacilli
isolated from wounds on day 1 of hospitalization in the Viet Nam conflict
(1). Aarabi (2) found that _Acinetobacter_ was the 2nd most common cause of
infection of missile-related head wounds in an Iranian report from data
collected during the Iran-Iraq conflict.

1. Tong MJ: Septic complications of war wounds. JAMA 1972;219:1044-47.

2. Aarabi B: Comparative study of bacteriological contamination between
primary and secondary exploration of missile head wounds. Neurosurgery
1987;20:610-19. - Mod.LL]
